node.text:
#MemorialDay. Never Forgotten, We Speak Their Names.

We honor our fallen by remembering their sacrifices, living with humility, & fighting for what they stood for. This country, our values, and beliefs, were built on a foundation of service and sacrifice. Please take a moment today to reflect on those sacrifices. And the current health crisis has shown that service and sacrifice don't always happen in a uniform. Thank you to everyone who has served and sacrificed in the name of service.

Thanks to the @navyudtsealmuseum for giving me the honor to speak some of the 304 names of Frogmen that have died since WWII. Too many of these names are close to me. Thank you to the following warriors that have had a positive impact on my life:

HM3 Lee Deal, May 17, 2006
SO2 Michael Bell, Apr 12 2006
AO2 Marc Lee, Aug 2, 2006
MA2 Michael Monsoor, Sep 29, 2006
SO2 Ryan Job, Sep 24, 2009
SOC JT Tumilson, Aug 6, 2011
SOC Darrik Benson, Aug 6, 2011
SOC Aaron Vaughn, Aug 6, 2011
SOC Mike Tatham, Oct 12, 2011
SOCS Ty Woods, Sep 12, 2012
SO1 Robert Guzzo, Nov 12, 2012
SO1 Nic Checque, Dec 8, 2012
SOC Chris Kyle, Feb 2, 2013
SOC Brad Cavner, Jun 23, 2014
SO1 Charles Keating IV, May 3, 2016
CDR Seth Stone, Sep 30, 2017
SSG Ronald Shurer, May 14, 2020

#HonorTheFallen

node.text:
Amazing views watching @thom_astro & @astro_kimbrough perform their 3rd spacewalk to upgrade the @ISS solar arrays. What's special about this operation is that the team has to time certain phases of their operation when the space station is in eclipse. The crew is being led by my classmate, @astro_jenni & Flight Director Pooja Jesrani.⠀
⠀
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dmI0nOnvbWw&ab_channel=NASA

Such a privilege to be a part of this team. Everyone worked around the clock to troubleshoot the installation issues of the solar array encountered last Wednesday. My Turtle classmate, @astro_jenni, and I watched the plan unfold in the Neutral Buoyancy Lab. Watch Jenni, and CapComs @astro_kutryk and @astro_feustel guide @astro_kimbrough & @thom_astro on their spacewalk as they finish the installation of the solar array. Semper Gumby!⠀
⠀
Watch the spacewalk live here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tukfEtyVpcU

node.text:
It's hard to articulate the conflicting emotions Memorial Day brings for me. I'm immensely privileged and grateful for life, and mindful of those who lost theirs. Today, I reflect and remember the sacrifices of those who fell in service, particularly the twelve I dearly miss. #memorialday 

Ryan Job, Jon Tumilson, Mike Monsoor, Seth Stone, Marc Lee, Chris Kyle, Nic Checque, Mike Bell, Lee Deal, Brad Cavner, Ty Woods, Mike Tatham.

node.text:
Mike Collins passed away today. No doubt thousands will recount his contributions to the @NASA Apollo program & human space exploration. But what I always admired most about Mr. Collins was his humility, and how his fame & privilege never changed his values or moral courage.⠀
⠀
My astronaut class had the privilege of meeting Mr. Collins during our training in 2019. He shared a story with us that I think reflects his wholesome character. He told us how after returning from Apollo 11, after his crewmates Neil Armstrong and Buzz Aldrin walked the surface of the moon, that he was offered an opportunity to return to the moon for a future Apollo mission, but the next time would be on the lunar surface. Mr. Collins politely declined the offer, saying he needed to be with his family now. Mr. Collins wasn't the type to boast of his accomplishments and I've always admired his humble leadership. Godspeed General Collins.

node.text: Lighting up the night sky like this never gets old. Congrats @astro_kimbrough, Aki Hoshide, @astro.megan & @thom_astro of the Endeavour Crew, @SpaceX, @NASA & everyone who supports behind the scenes. The mission isn't over, docking is next. I'm looking forward to supporting you all at the International Space Station from Mission Control Center Houston.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jonny Kim on April 09, 2021.

node.text: And a great way to end a day. After watching a successful launch of the crew to the @iss, I had the privilege to work with Ike, one of our spacewalking task instructors, to develop contingency procedures for the International Space Station. He came up with a great solution to quickly installing a piece of equipment that I hadn't thought of. It's always amazing at the solution sets that come up when you have a team of operators and leaders from various backgrounds. Teamwork crushes problems.

node.text:
Great way to start a day. Watching my friend, Mark Vande Hei, launch to the @ISS with his Russian crewmates, Novitskiy & Dubrov. I'm honored to be their increment lead (ground liaison) for their Expedition. @SpaceX crew-2 following shortly. Intl collaboration rocks.⠀
⠀
Repost @NASA: Liftoff! Mark Vande Hei of @NASAAstronauts and cosmonauts Oleg Novitskiy & Pyotr Dubrov launched on their Soyuz spacecraft from the Baikonur Cosmodrome in Kazakhstan. They'll join the Expedition 64 crew aboard the @ISS.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Jonny Kim on March 22, 2021. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and indoor.

node.text:
Back to my @usnavy roots! I had an opportunity to work with Captain Jay Young of Naval Sea Systems Command and @nasa to demonstrate the Diver Augmented Vision Display (DAVD) system, which is a heads-up display and augmented-reality system that is being developed for deep-sea salvage operations and may have the potential of influencing future HUD designs for our lunar spacesuit (called xEVA) for our upcoming #Artemis missions.

We used the Neutral Buoyancy Lab in Houston, TX to modify our buoyancy to match the equivalent weight we would feel on the lunar surface (which is 1/6th of earth's gravity). We also turned off the lights in order to see how the heads-up display could enhance low-light conditions and navigate astronauts with loadable waypoints (like a video game). The HUD also displayed telemetry that could be useful for a spacewalker on the lunar surface (think mission elapsed time, time remaining of life-support consumables, suit pressure, etc).

I had a great time working with Captain Jay Young, LCDR Beautyman, and my fellow classmate @zenanaut on this project. We of course can't do any of the work we do without the great support of the technicians, engineers, and divers that work behind the scenes. Credit to @nasa and @usnavy for the pictures.
